==English==
===Etymology===
{{webster}}

From Old English [[fyst|fȳst]].  Cognate with [[w:Dutch language|Dutch]][[Category:Dutch derivations]] vuist, [[w:Old High German|Old High German]][[Category:Old High German derivations]] fst, [[w:German language|German]][[Category:German derivations]] faust, and probably to [[w:Latin|Latin]][[Category:Latin derivations]] pugnus, [[w:Greek language|Greek]][[Category:Greek derivations]] fist, with the fist. Compare with [[pugnacious]], [[pigmy]].

===Pronunciation===
*fĭst, /fɪst/, /<tt>fIst</tt>/
*{{audio|en-us-fist.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
'''fist''' (plural: '''fists''')

#[[hand]] with the [[finger]]s [[clench]]ed or [[curl]]ed inward
#:''The boxer's '''fists''' rained down on his opponent in the last round.''
#(''printing'') the pointing [[hand]] symbol
#(''ham radio'') the characteristic signaling rhythm of an individual [[telegraph]] or [[continuous wave|CW]] operator

